Evaluation Takeaways: [10 marks]¶

a) Based on your results above, is there any performance difference between the two algorithms? If so which one is faster? [1 mark]

Ans: Apriori beats fpgrowth as minimum supports grows.

b) What impact does changing the minimum support value has and why? [2 marks]

Ans: Minimum support reduces and eleminates the elements/combinations below a certain level. As minimum support grows, it takes more time for computations.

c) The dataset contains around 7,500 transactions. Why were very few frequent itemsets returned? [2 marks]

Ans: After data cleaning and eliminating elements below minimum support, the algorithm picks out only the frequent items

#Create candidate 1 item sets
def createC1(dataSet):
    '''
    Add your code here. This function will receive data set as input and return the C1 set.
    '''
    C1 = []
    for row in dataSet:
        for rowItem in row:
            if not [rowItem] in C1:
                C1.append([rowItem])            
    C1.sort()
    return list(map(frozenset, C1))
In [287]:
#Looking for k-frequent itemsets
def selectLk(dataSet,Ck,minSupport):
    '''
    Add your code here. This function will receive data set, Ck and minimum support value. The funtion will return pruned items from Ck.
    '''
    CkUpdated = []
    sup = {}
    supCount = {}
    for rowItem in dataSet:
        for Item in Ck:
            if Item.issubset(rowItem):
                if not Item in supCount: supCount[Item]=1
                else: supCount[Item] += 1
    numItems = float(len(dataSet))
    for key in supCount:
        support = supCount[key]/numItems
        if support >= minSupport:
            CkUpdated.insert(0,key)
        sup[key] = support
    return CkUpdated, sup
In [288]:
def createCk(Lk,k): # Lk: Frequent itemsets containing k items
    '''
    Add your code here. This function will receive Lk frequent items set and it's count. The function will return Ck.
    '''
    Ck = []
    for i in range(len(Lk)):
        for j in range(i+1, len(Lk)): 
            L1 = list(Lk[i])[:k-2]; L2 = list(Lk[j])[:k-2]
            L1.sort(); L2.sort()
            if L1==L2: 
                Ck.append(Lk[i] | Lk[j])
    return Ck
In [289]:
#Apriori algorithm
def apriori(dataSet,minSupport):
    #create C1
    C1 = createC1(dataSet)
    L1, support = selectLk(list(map(set, dataSet)), C1, minSupport)
    L = [L1]
    k = 2
   #Iterative create and select Ck & Lk iteratively.
    while (len(L[k-2]) > 0):
        Ck = createCk(L[k-2], k)
        Lk, supK = selectLk(list(map(set, dataSet)), Ck, minSupport)
        support.update(supK)
        L.append(Lk)
        k += 1

    y = []
    for i in L:
      for j in i:
        y.append(list(j))
    return y
